        "header": "1Introduction",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2605.30834/2605.30834v1/x1.png",
                "caption": "Figure 1:Hide-and-Seek Failure Detection.Failure trajectories contain a substantial amount of normal actions before failure onset, yet only a trajectory-level label is available during training, leaving the temporal structure entirely unknown (top).\nFrom this coarse supervision,\nHide-and-Seek discovers the most failure-indicative actions (e.g., the failure onset and subsequent critical event) by contrasting scores across and within trajectories, naturally separating normal execution from the failure phase without any step-level annotation (bottom).",
                "position": 398
            }
        ]
    },
