        "header": "4Hide-and-Seek Failure Detection",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2605.30834/2605.30834v1/x2.png",
                "caption": "Figure 2:Overall framework.Given a failure-success trajectory pair(τf,τs)(\\tau_{f},\\tau_{s}),\nthe detectorfϕf_{\\phi}produces per-step failure scoressts_{t}for both failure and successful trajectories.ℒinter\\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{inter}}(Eq.2) enforces that the most failure-indicative action in the failure trajectoryτf\\tau_{f}ranks higher than the hardest false-positive in the successful trajectoryτs\\tau_{s}.ℒintra\\mathcal{L}_{\\mathrm{intra}}(Eq.3) defines a proxy failure onset astonset=arg⁡maxt⁡(st−st−1)t_{\\mathrm{onset}}=\\arg\\max_{t}(s_{t}-s_{t-1}), and enforces temporal separation withinτf\\tau_{f}by encouraging average post-onset scores to exceed average pre-onset scores.\nThe two losses jointly shape the score dynamics so thatsts_{t}stays low during normal execution while sharply rising attonsett_{\\mathrm{onset}}in failure trajectories.",
                "position": 531
            }
        ]
    },
